text: Proposed policy changes to the Gulf of Mexico red snapper IFQ program: Evaluating diﬀerential impacts by participant type Andrew Ropickia,∗ a Department of Agricultural Economics, Texas A&M University, College Station, TX 77843, USA b Oceans Program, Environmental Defense Fund, Austin, TX 78701, USA c Food and Resource Economics Department, University of Florida, Gainesville, FL 32611, USA Keywords: Individual ﬁshing quotas (IFQs) Allocation Concentration Investors Magnuson-Stevens Act The Gulf of Mexico Fishery Management Council (GMFMC) Reef Fish Amendment 26 established individual ﬁshing quota (IFQ) man- agement of the commercial red snapper ﬁshery in the Gulf of Mexico (GMFMC, 2006). The program, implemented by NOAA Fisheries in 2007, was the ﬁrst catch share management program in the Gulf of Mexico. IFQ management was adopted to reduce overcapacity in the commercial red snapper ﬁshery and eliminate problems associated with derby style ﬁshing (GMFMC, 2006). As required by the Magnuson- Stevens Fishery Conservation and Management Act (MSA), a review of the program was conducted during 2012 (ﬁve years post implementa- tion) and found IFQ management was successful on both fronts as it led to fewer vessels (i.e., more eﬃcient use of capital resources) and year- round ﬁshing that has increased and stabilized dockside price (GMFMC, 2013; Solís et al. 2014a, 2015). Although IFQ management ended the race to ﬁsh and decreased overcapacity in the ﬁshery, issues have been raised over the eﬀective- ness of the program in meeting other management objectives including impacts on ﬁshery participants. Larkinc journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/ocecoaman Ocean and Coastal Management The U.S. commercial red snapper IFQ program was the ﬁrst catch share management system implemented in the Gulf of Mexico. The program has been successful in meeting its major goals of ending derby-style ﬁshing and reducing overcapacity in the harvest sector, but several concerns regarding the socioeconomic impacts of the program have been raised. To address these concerns, the management agency initiated a ﬁshery management plan amendment to develop potential modiﬁcations to the program. This analysis describes the proposed policy changes, identiﬁes the key outcomes, and assesses the impacts on distinct participant types using historic harvest data, quota trading patterns, and existing estimates of industry concentration. There are three implied regulatory objectives, as all proposed modiﬁcations would either increase ownership of shares by harvesters, limit con- solidation in the harvest sector, or increase harvest ﬂexibility. The corresponding eﬀects on stakeholders could vary quite substantially as each objective and the associated alternative policies would aﬀect the size and composition of multiple markets that collectively aﬀect socioeconomic outcomes. The approach to evaluating existing catch share programs and the associated ﬁndings in this paper are important for management agencies charged with adhering to federal policies and guidance concerning distributional outcomes. rates in the eastern Gulf of Mexico (NMFS, 2015); quota was initially allocated to ﬁshers based on catch histories so less quota was allocated to ﬁshermen in areas where red snapper were less abundant historically (i.e., Florida peninsula). Since IFQ implementation, however, red snapper stocks along the west Florida shelf have rebounded and many ﬁshermen that target other reef ﬁsh species have needed to discard red snapper if they have not acquired additional quota. Although discard ratios for red snapper (discarded:landed) have fallen in the region since implementation of the IFQ program, they remain ﬁve to 15 times higher than ratios found in the rest of the Gulf of Mexico (NMFS, 2015). Another issue is the increase in quota owners that no longer ﬁsh. By 2014, 29% of the quota was held in IFQ shareholder accounts ineligible to ﬁsh because they did not hold a valid commercial reef ﬁsh permit but were eligible to lease or sell quota; conversely, 39% of red snapper landings were by vessels associated with shareholder accounts that did not own quota and leased in their harvest/landing privileges (NMFS, 2015). As such, a related issue is an increasing rate of lease-dependent ﬁshermen on the associated sustainability and resiliency of coastal ﬁshing communities. This is an issue that is essentially about who ﬁshes and who beneﬁts – that is, a distributional issue and one that is not

unique to this ﬁshery (McCay et al., 1995; Brandt, 2005; Dawson, 2005; Knapp, 2011; Olson, 2011; Criddle and Strong, 2013; Pascoe et al., 2014; Apgar-Kurtz, 2015; Bodwitch, 2017). To address distributional issues, other IFQ programs in U.S. ﬁsheries have included: area speciﬁc quota (Paciﬁc Coast groundﬁsh trawl and North Paciﬁc halibut and sableﬁsh), quota speciﬁc to vessel classes and/or harvesting strategies (Bering Sea pollock, BSAI king and tanner crab, North Paciﬁc halibut and sableﬁsh, Paciﬁc Coast groundﬁsh trawl), owner-on-board re- quirements for harvesting (North Paciﬁc halibut and sableﬁsh, Paciﬁc Coast ﬁxed-gear sableﬁsh), and requiring that quota share transactions include all other associated ﬁsheries (Northeast multispecies ground- ﬁsh, and general category Atlantic scallops) (Holland et al., 2015). For comparison, the only current distributional restriction for the Gulf of Mexico red snapper IFQ program is a cap on share ownership.

To address IFQ issues with respect to distributional impacts, the GMFMC initiated a ﬁshery management plan amendment with the goal of proposing modiﬁcations to the program. Following a ﬁve-year review of the red snapper IFQ program, mandated by the MSA, the GMFMC appointed an ad hoc red snapper IFQ advisory panel, made up of commercial ﬁshers and ﬁsh house owners, to recommend potential changes to improve the program. The GMFMC then evaluated and modiﬁed the panel's list of potential changes at a series of meetings in 2014. The resulting scoping document identiﬁed several potential modiﬁcations (GMFMC, 2015), and many are now formalized into proposed Reef Fish Amendments 36A and 36B.1 In this study, we evaluate the primary proposed changes using a mix of data from, and research on, the commercial red snapper ﬁshery, trading under the IFQ program and other IFQ ﬁsheries in the Gulf of Mexico. The evaluation also looks at the proposed changes with regards to current federal ﬁsheries regulations (i.e., the MSA), stated goals of the IFQ program, and the NOAA Catch Share Policy (NOAA Fisheries, 2010). The next section provides background on the ﬁshery and the IFQ program and is followed by a description of the proposed changes and the results of analyses of their potential impacts on the ﬁshery and its participants. The article closes with concluding remarks. Red snapper is part of the management unit of the Reef Fish Fishery Management Plan (FMP) in the Gulf of Mexico. The ﬁshery is managed by NOAA Fisheries through the GMFMC. The FMP covers numerous snapper and grouper species as well as amberjacks, triggerﬁsh, tileﬁsh, and several other species. For commercial reef ﬁsh ﬁshermen, red snapper, vermillion snapper, and red grouper are the most harvested commercial species by weight.

In 1988 the red snapper ﬁshery was found to be overﬁshed and undergoing overﬁshing (Goodyear, 1992); in response, a total allowable catch (TAC) was set in 1990 as the main means of limiting overﬁshing. The use of a TAC to manage harvest continued through 2006. The TAC was set annually with 51% of the TAC allocated to commercial ﬁsh- ermen that held a required reef ﬁsh permit (commercial quota) and 49% allocated to recreational ﬁshermen (recreational quota). In addi- tion to a TAC, regulators imposed a moratorium on issuance of new reef ﬁsh permits and red snapper endorsements that eﬀectively limited di- rected red snapper harvesting to 136 vessels (GMFMC, 2006).2 TAC 1 The original scoping document (GMFMC, 2015) only considered changes to the red snapper IFQ program. Revisions to the original document led to proposed Amendments 36A and 36B and broadened the scope to include both the red snapper and grouper- tileﬁsh IFQ programs. Amendment 36B includes the proposals discussed in this paper and continues to evolve. For conciseness, this analysis focuses on the potential impacts on the red snapper ﬁshery only, but the techniques used are applicable to the grouper-tileﬁsh and other IFQ programs. 2 The red snapper endorsement system included 136 Class 1 endorsements, limited to 2000 pound trip limits, and 628 Class 2 endorsements limited to 200 pound trip limits. In eﬀect, Class 1 endorsements authorized directed red snapper harvest and Class 2 en- dorsements authorized landing incidental red snapper harvest.

management of the red snapper ﬁshery led to shortened seasons. Be- tween 1996 and 2003 the average commercial red snapper season was only 77 days stretched across 10-day monthly mini-seasons until quotas were attained (NMFS, 2008). The race to ﬁsh caused by TAC manage- ment led to ﬂooded markets and lower dockside prices due to market gluts (Weninger and Waters, 2003). In 2007, NOAA Fisheries im- plemented IFQ management in the Gulf of Mexico commercial red snapper ﬁshery to reduce overcapacity and eliminate the problems as- sociated with derby ﬁshing. In 2010, the IFQ program was extended to several other commercial grouper and tileﬁsh species. Quota in the ﬁshery is managed through two components: shares and allocation. Shares are the percentage of the total commercial quota owned by individual entities and represent a perpetual (but revocable) privilege as long as the program exists. Allocation is the annual harvest privilege (in pounds) associated with shares and is the amount of red snapper a ﬁsher can legally land or trade annually. A shareholder's al- location is determined by multiplying their share by the annual com- mercial quota. Share ownership is restricted to no more than 6.0203% of the total commercial quota for any unique entity; however, there are currently no restrictions on the amount of annual allocation that can be accumulated by an entity (NMFS, 2014).

Both share and allocation are tradeable with share transactions re- presenting a permanent transfer of quota (the buyer receives all future allocation associated with the share transferred) while allocation transactions are on an annual basis (a lease), only involving current year harvest privileges; any allocation that goes unharvested does not carry over into future years. Share was initially awarded to 554 ﬁshing entities based on catch history. For the ﬁrst ﬁve years of the IFQ pro- gram (2007–2011), quota ownership (share and allocation) was limited to those entities holding a valid Gulf of Mexico commercial reef ﬁsh permit. In 2012, the requirement was lifted allowing all U.S. citizens and permanent legal residents to purchase and sell both share and al- location; however, the commercial reef ﬁsh permit is still required to commercially harvest red snapper (NMFS, 2013). The MSA requires that all limited access privilege programs, in- cluding IFQ programs, be evaluated within ﬁve years of their im- plementation. The review found that the IFQ program led to a reduction in the size of the commercial ﬂeet from 443 vessels in 2006 to 368 vessels in 2011 (GMFMC, 2013). This decrease may, however, be modest given a recent ﬂeet capacity utilization analysis estimated that 75 vertical line vessels could have harvested the entire 2011 commer- cial quota (Solís et al., 2014b). IFQ management also eliminated the race to ﬁsh, such that landings are spread more evenly throughout the year, consequently stabilizing dockside prices for red snapper. During the ﬁrst year of IFQ management, 2007, the inﬂation-adjusted dockside the previous ﬁve years price rose 24.6% above the average of inﬂation-adjusted dockside prices increased another (2002–2006); 15.9% between 2007 and 2014 (NMFS, 2015).

The commercial red snapper ﬁshery, while distinct from the re- creational sector, is also heterogeneous with respect to target species, ﬁshing gears, ﬁshing-dependent communities, and participant types. This analysis deﬁnes six diﬀerent participant types that consider ﬁshing status, share ownership, and leasing behavior (Table 1) (Ropicki, 2014). By subdividing participants in this manner, the analysis evaluates how diﬀerent participant types, with diﬀerent ﬁshery practices and beha- viors, will respond to proposed management modiﬁcations. Fig. 1 presents the allocation held (by investors and allocation brokers) and the allocation ﬁshed (by allocation-dependent ﬁshers, investor ﬁshers, share ﬁshers, and supplementers) as a percentage of total annual quota at year end. Investor accounts continue to grow in terms of the percentage of the total commercial quota owned as share; at the same time the per- centage of total harvest by allocation-dependent account holders has also grown. Some IFQ participants have multiple shareholder accounts and hold their quota in accounts without an associated reef ﬁsh permit but transfer the quota to aﬃliated accounts with a permit to harvest their quota. Finally, although the role of allocation brokers has increased through time they still only trade a small amount of the annual allocation.

The proposed modiﬁcations to the red snapper IFQ Program are categorized into three groups for evaluation based on the objective of the regulatory change: 1) to increase share ownership among har- vesters, 2) to limit allocation/harvest consolidation, and 3) to increase harvest ﬂexibility. The evaluation focuses on the potential eﬀects on IFQ participants, IFQ program goals, and adherence to rules and guidelines regarding catch shares management programs in U.S. federal waters. The evaluation utilizes secondary data and results from pre- vious evaluations of the ﬁshery and studies of the trading markets for both allocation and landings. 3.1. These proposals limit the role of investors in the ﬁshery but diﬀer by how they would increase share ownership – that is, by either eﬀectively requiring a reef ﬁsh permit (Proposals 1 and 2) or redistributing shares (Proposals 3 and 4). The implications of each are discussed in turn. 3.1.1. Requiring a permit

Proposal 1 would impact investors (Table 1) that desire to change their level of long-term investment in the ﬁshery. An examination of online ﬁshing permit brokerage sites found eight permits for sale for an average of $9375 ($7500 to $10,000) on boatsandquota.com between August 2015 and July 2016. For some investors, this additional capital expense might not be feasible (shrinking the share market); however, it might not dissuade well-capitalized investors. If so, then the policy might not increase ownership by harvesters. Proposal 2 would also directly aﬀect investors, but only those looking to increase their long- run investment or those that are already above the cap that would need to disinvest or buy a permit. Proposal 2 does not prohibit the entry of more investors. As such, these proposals are less an attempt to increase ownership among active harvesters than to limit the role of investors in the ﬁshery. Moreover, these proposals do not address whether ﬁshing would be required under the permit in order to retain shares. To quantitatively assess the impact of Proposal 1, we calculate the internal rate of return (IRR) - a well-known ﬁnancial metric of the re- lative desirability of an asset - for investors contemplating diﬀerent quantities of share purchases. (1) IRRs were ﬁrst calculated with the Initial Investment only including the share purchase cost to reﬂect the status quo, and then with Initial Investment including both the share purchase costs and the cost of a permit (i.e., $9375) to reﬂect the impact of the proposed change. These calculations assume Allocation Income occurring at the beginning of each year (shares owned in pounds multiplied by the allocation price) and terminal values in the ﬁnal period (shares owned multiplied by share price plus average permit cost). Allocation and share prices used in the calculation were 2014 mean values of $3 and $34 per pound, respec- tively (NMFS, 2015). Additional assumptions include a 10-year invest- ment horizon, allocation, share, and permit values do not appreciate in real terms, and the aggregate commercial sector quota does not change. The ﬁgure shows that requiring the purchase of a reef ﬁsh permit would decrease the proﬁt- ability of future share purchases by investors, and signiﬁcantly so for those considering small purchases.

Requiring a reef ﬁsh permit to retain or buy shares held above a cap would reduce the value of the investment to investors but it would not change the proﬁtability of share currently owned by investors that are under the cap. And small shareholders would still be able to purchase shares at no additional cost up to the cap. If the requirement does lead to investors exiting the share market, the decreased demand for shares could lower prices to levels where allocation-dependent ﬁshers and supplementers can become shareholders. However, it is also possible that investor ﬁshers and share ﬁshers might replace investors in the share purchasing market. Such an outcome could be detrimental to allocation-dependent ﬁshers and supplementers because it could lead to less allocation being available as more is harvested by share owners. 3.1.2. Redistributing shares The scoping document provided no speciﬁcs on how the redis- tribution proposals (use-it or lose-it and lease-to-own) would be im- plemented, but the basic premise of these proposals is that in any given year during which a shareholder sells some, or all, of their share as allocation, they would forfeit x% of that share at year end (barring any hardship). The use-it or lose-it proposal would lead to some percentage of share sold as allocation being redistributed to all other ﬁshers or certain groups of ﬁshers based on some predetermined formula,3 while the lease-to-own proposal would entail lease dependent ﬁshers and lease supplementers earning share over time based on harvest of allo- cation while investors and investor ﬁshers would lose share based on continuing allocation sales. The lease-to-own proposal is essentially an oﬀshoot of the use-it or lose-it proposal; the latter (Proposal 3) would

3 The analysis of a use-it or lose-it provision presented in this paper focuses only on the forfeiture of share sold as allocation and not forfeiture of share that is unused (neither sold as allocation or harvested). The scoping document (GMFMC, 2015) outlined use-it or lose-it provisions as a potential response to public testimony regarding the role of in- vestors in the ﬁshery. A use-it or lose-it provision that required the forfeiture of unused share (neither sold as allocation or harvested) would limit the ability of ﬁshers to forgo harvesting in the current period to reinvest in the stock and increase the size of future harvests. Currently, reinvesting in the stock by forgoing harvesting in the current year does not seem to be a common strategy as, on average, 97.5% of the quota was harvested during the ﬁrst nine years of the red snapper IFQ program (NMFS, 2016). have share forfeited by non-harvesters (investors and investor ﬁshers) allocated among all harvesters while the lease-to-own program (Pro- posal 4) would only allocate forfeited shares to entities that purchased allocation (allocation-dependent ﬁshers and supplementers). It seems unlikely that Proposal 3 (use-it or lose-it) or 4 (lease-to- own) would be implemented retroactively or all at once. Retroactive implementation would be diﬃcult given both the large amount of share held by investor and investor-ﬁsher accounts and the presence of en- tities with multiple accounts that can move allocation easily between accounts. In 2014, 29% of quota share was held by investor accounts that would likely protest Proposal 3 as unjust, especially since it could be implemented without compensation to the owner, but also because open leasing provisions were developed as a mechanism to enhance ﬁshery eﬃciency and mitigate discards (GMFMC, 2006). Retroactive implementation would also prohibit entities with multiple accounts to keep share they harvest across all accounts. Alternatively, by enacting the rules relative to future harvest, these entities would have time to move shares to accounts with reef ﬁsh permits.

There would also be problems associated with sudden, or all-at- once, implementation of these proposals. Under Proposal 3, investors would likely sell prior to implementation to avoid forfeiture which could also ﬂood the share market and depress prices. Under Proposal 4, investors could simply ﬁnd a new buyer prior to triggering the for- feiture requirement (e.g., if x years of ﬁsher A selling allocation to ﬁsher B led to share redistribution from A to B, then A would simply start selling allocation to ﬁsher C prior to year x). Investors could also cir- cumvent the requirement by transferring allocation through an inter- mediary. Finally, investor ﬁshers could stop selling allocation alto- gether, supplementers and allocation- dependent ﬁshers. Given the potential pitfalls associated with retro- active or sudden implementation of these proposals, only the potential for gradual implementation is analyzed further. These proposals are evaluated by considering how forfeiting a portion of an investor's share each year would impact their IRR. The Initial Share Value is the share price after the redistribution policy is initiated and represents an investor's opportunity cost associated with continuing to own quota. At higher forfeiture rates (25% and 50%) investors would likely rush to sell their share to avoid large losses. However, at the lower forfeiture rates (2% and 5%), investors could hold onto their current share investments that would continue to generate positive returns. This analysis also reveals intrinsic share price ﬂoors for diﬀerent for- feiture rates given the assumptions – that is, a 2% forfeiture rate is not likely to decrease share price to $25 per pound. At that price, investors selling their share would need to reinvest their proceeds in an invest- ment returning 12.04% to be as well oﬀ as they would be holding their share and selling their annual allocation for an additional 10 years (even after accounting for annual forfeiture). Given this required return is above the 10.28% return they were already anticipating from their share investment prior to share redistribution, it seems unlikely that share prices would fall that far. As shown in Table 2, forfeiture rates have signiﬁcant eﬀects on the proﬁtability of shares as an investment. Moreover, high forfeiture rates could shrink allocation markets as investors would likely sell their shares to avoid forfeitures and new share purchasers would harvest their shares to avoid forfeitures. High forfeiture rates could also lead to investor ﬁshers harvesting more of their own allocation to avoid for- feiting share. High for- feiture rates could leave allocation-dependent ﬁshers without share and without a viable allocation market. If a lease-to-own provision were being considered, where all forfeited quota share went to allocation buying ﬁshers, low forfeiture rates would probably provide the most viable path towards increasing share ownership among allocation-de- pendent ﬁshers. If forfeiture rates were low enough to keep investors from selling their shareholdings, it would decrease the likelihood that a small group of well-ﬁnanced share ﬁshers and investor ﬁshers could purchase investor share prior to forfeiture and harvest it directly, thereby signiﬁcantly shrinking the allocation market and the potential for lease-to-own relationships. 3.1.3. Comparing proposals to increase ownership Proposals to increase share ownership among harvesters diﬀer with respect to adherence to federal catch share regulations and policy guidance. Table 3 compares how the proposals might impact diﬀerent IFQ participant types and markets. While the permit requirement pro- posals would only impact investors' future share purchases (unless they are above the cap), the share redistribution proposals would impact investors’ current shareholdings. Another important diﬀerence is that the share redistribution proposals impact all share investors equally while the permit requirement proposal impacts are based on investment size. Lastly, all four proposals could potentially shrink the allocation market depending on how they are implemented.

The permit requirement and share redistribution proposals would not directly impact the red snapper IFQ program's goals of ending overcapacity and derby ﬁshing conditions since it would inﬂuence quota ownership and not ﬁshing eﬀort. The proposal's adherence to NOAA's ﬁshery management policies and guidelines is, however, diﬃ- cult to evaluate. For instance, if permit requirements or share redistribution policies led to fewer outside investors in the ﬁshery, the allocation market could shrink and adversely impact allo- cation-dependent ﬁshers and allocation supplementers by limiting the supply of allocation. Consolidation of allocation among a smaller group of harvesters could also negatively impact ﬁshing communities that are comprised of allocation-dependent ﬁshers, which may not meet the requirements of MSA National Standard 8 (MSA, 2014): Thus, while the objective of these proposals adheres to federal catch share policies (by not creating speculative ﬁnancial instruments out of ﬁshing privileges), the consequences of enacting such policies could be counter to the legal requirements of MSA (i.e., the need to protect ﬁshing communities). 3.2. Limiting consolidation

Although reduction of overcapacity was a primary goal of the red snapper IFQ program, the GMFMC has considered measures to prevent further concentration of harvest and harvest privileges (GMFMC, 2017). Two recent studies examined the concentration of red snapper landings using aggregate standard measures. Agar et al. (2014) compared the Gini coeﬃcient of vessel landings for ﬁve years prior to IFQ im- plementation (2002–2006) with that of the ﬁrst ﬁve years under IFQ management and found that it fell from 0.80 to 0.75 (where 0 re- presents equality and 1 represents extreme inequality), indicating that IFQ management decreased vessel-level harvest concentration. Mitchell (2016) evaluated IFQ account level landings data and found that the Herﬁndahl-Hirschman Index ranged from 224 to 348 annually – values not indicative of strong market concentration. Agar et al. (2014) cor- roborated this ﬁnding at the shareholder level. The lack of concentra- tion found in these studies indicates that concentration has become less of an issue under IFQ management. Capping the allocation held (Proposal 5) or landed (Proposal 6) could decrease harvest capability and capacity utilization in addition to limiting concentration. Although consolidation is the concern, reducing harvest capability contradicts the overall program goal of reducing overcapacity (GMFMC, 2006). Without knowing the level of the caps, it is diﬃcult to assess how such policies would impact ﬂeet consolidation or capacity utilization; however, the MSA National Standard 4 (MSA, 2014) states: 5. Establish a cap on red snapper IFQ allocation held by an entity, or 6. Establish a cap on red snapper IFQ allocation landed by a single Both the MSA National Standards and the LAPP provisions aﬃrm the purpose of the MSA is the conservation and management of the nation's ﬁshery resources, not the development of speculative ﬁ- nancial instruments or investment opportunities for individuals or businesses not substantially participating in the ﬁshery.

Conservation and management measures shall, consistent with the conservation requirements of this Act (including the prevention of overﬁshing and rebuilding of overﬁshed stocks), take into account the importance of ﬁshery resources to ﬁshing communities by uti- lizing economic and social data that meet the requirement of para- graph (2) [i.e., National Standard 2], in order to (a) provide for the sustained participation of such communities, and (b) to the extent practicable, minimize adverse economic impacts on such commu- nities. The proposed changes designed to limit consolidation are to: While it is possible that enacting one of the proposals to increase share ownership among harvesters could lead to consolidation of har- vest, given that consolidation of harvest was not recognized as a point of concern in the ﬁshery prior to IFQ implementation, and analysis has found that concentration of harvest has declined since IFQ im- plementation (Agar et al., 2014), the current share cap appears suﬃ- cient to satisfy MSA National Standard 4 and other MSA provisions related to share concentration (MSA Section 303a(c) (5) (D)), and concentration in allocation (leased or landed) does not appear to be an issue. However, it is worth noting that each of the proposals to increase share ownership among harvesters analyzed previously could decrease the size of the allocation market and conceivably lead to harvest con- solidation, potentially among investor and share ﬁshers, if enacted. 3.3. Increasing harvest ﬂexibility Proposal 7 would decrease the costs of entering the ﬁshery and potentially allow commercial vessels without reef ﬁsh permits to har- vest red snapper allocation. It would also allow recreational and re- creational for-hire ﬁshers to harvest commercial allocation (i.e., inter- sector allocation trading). Proposal 8 would increase harvester ﬂexibility with regards to when they choose to land allocation. 3.3.1. Allow harvesting without a permit

The eﬀects of allowing accounts without a reef ﬁsh permit to harvest allocation depends largely on whether intersector trading will be al- lowed. Since 2012 the general public, including recreational and for- hire ﬁshers, has been able to trade quota and allocation but not to harvest allocation without a commercial reef ﬁsh permit. Proposal 7 would lower the cost of entering the ﬁshery as new en- trants would avoid the estimated $9375 permit fee (opposite of pro- posal 1). A 2012 survey (Boen and Keithly, 2012) found that most red snapper IFQ participants believed the IFQ program had made entering the ﬁshery more diﬃcult. This policy would lessen the ﬁnancial burden of new ﬁshers. Although Proposal 7 would beneﬁt future entrants, it would harm current permit owners by eliminating a valuable asset; the only current participant group that would not be negatively impacted would be investors, who could beneﬁt if the proposal led to new en- trants into the ﬁshery and more participation in the share and alloca- tion markets. This proposal would also likely impact reef ﬁsh permit holders that do not harvest red snapper and instead target other reef ﬁsh species not currently managed using IFQ such as vermillion snapper. This group would also see the value of their reef ﬁsh permit disappear. And if the proposal were implemented in such a manner that it only applied to red snapper ﬁshers, it could increase bycatch as new red snapper harvesters (lacking a permit) would not be able to legally retain other reef ﬁsh species caught while targeting red snapper.

The adoption of proposal 7 without intersector allocation trading could lead to outcomes inconsistent with the stated IFQ goal of de- creasing overcapacity in the red snapper ﬁshery since removing the reef ﬁsh permit requirement could lead to new entrants; however, joining the ﬁshery is still costly (vessel, gear, docking, quota, etc.) and it seems unlikely removing this requirement would lead to a large increase in active ﬁshers. The proposal does not contradict ﬁsheries regulations regarding catch share programs, but if the permit requirement were removed only for red snapper, new non-permitted red snapper ﬁshers 7. If so, Proposal 7 could violate MSA National Standard 9 (MSA, 2014) which states: If the reef ﬁsh permit requirement was simply lifted it would fa- cilitate intersector trading of harvest privileges; recreational and for- hire ﬁshers would be able to purchase share and allocation and harvest the allocation pounds associated with each. This scenario would ne- gatively impact allocation-dependent ﬁshers and possibly allocation supplementers since it would increase demand for share and allocation. It is likely that recreational and for-hire ﬁshers purchasing share would not do so with the intent of selling the associated allocation, so the supply of allocation would fall. Additionally, intersector trading would decrease the amount of the TAC harvested by the commercial sector if any ﬁshermen or entities sold to recreational sectors. 3.3.2. Allow allocation to roll-over

Currently, ﬁshers must either sell or ﬁsh their allocation by year end or it expires worthless. This deadline has led to a small race-to-ﬁsh occurring during the month of December. During the ﬁrst eight years of the program, 11.6% of all red snapper landings have occurred in December, 39% more than if landings were evenly spaced throughout the year (NMFS, 2015). This race to harvest allocation before expiration has negatively impacted dockside prices by an average of 6.5% (NMFS, 2013, 2014, 2015). Proposal 8 supports the initial program goal of reducing problems associated with derby-style ﬁshing, which can be exacerbated by external forces that aﬀect the allocation markets, and would not be in opposition to the MSA National Standards or the NOAA Catch Share Policy.4

If Proposal 8 allowed unused allocation to be harvested in the subsequent calendar year, the proposal would beneﬁt all allocation holders, but allocation-dependent ﬁshers and allocation brokers stand to beneﬁt most. As an example, in 2013 the GMFMC increased the red snapper quota nearly 1.2 million pounds on September 30th, a 30% increase above the annual TAC. This increase caused average ex-vessel prices to fall 22.2% between September and December due to ﬁshers rushing to harvest allocation before it expired (NMFS, 2014). During the same period allocation prices fell 26.2% (NMFS, 2015). While shareholder losses were oﬀset with additional allocation, allocation- dependent ﬁshers and allocation brokers that owned allocation saw their margins erode. With declining ex-vessel prices, the relative cost of allocation purchased in September increased from 66.6% of September ex-vessel price to 85.6% of December ex-vessel price (NMFS, 2014, 2015). A roll-over provision would lessen the price risk faced by allo- cation-dependent ﬁshers and allocation brokers, but could increase administrative costs associated with keeping track of share and allo- cation balances through time. While this example was caused by a management decision, which could have been delayed to coincide with the next management cycle, other external events can lead to market gluts in the allocation market (e.g., oil spills that close ﬁshing grounds).

The New England Fishery Management Council addressed this concern by allowing 10% of groundﬁsh sectors' unused initial allocations to roll over into the subsequent year, provided that the sum of 10% of all sectors' allocations plus the next year's annual catch limit does not exceed the next year's acceptable biological catch (81 Fed. Reg. 26412, 26527). The North Paciﬁc Fishery Management Council adopted a similar adjustment policy for the Paciﬁc halibut/ sableﬁsh IFQ program allowing 10% of unused annual allocation to roll over. These measures address the diﬃculty of harvesting exact annual allocations and provide ﬂex- ibility without signiﬁcant risk of overharvesting (NPFMC, 2016). Conservation and management measures shall, to the extent prac- ticable, (a) minimize bycatch and (b) to the extent bycatch cannot be avoided, minimize the mortality of such bycatch. 4. Summary and conclusions

Fishery management systems that assign harvest privileges can be controversial, but documented successes at meeting key objectives have provided support for the continued implementation and use of such systems. The commercial red snapper IFQ program in the Gulf of Mexico is no exception. The program was initiated in 2007 and eval- uated after ﬁve years. The review concluded that the program has met key objectives of ending overﬁshing and spreading out the season, but raised concerns over the distribution of beneﬁts, long-run impacts on distinct ﬁshing sectors, and success at meeting all National Standards deﬁned in the Magnuson-Stevens Act. To help address these concerns, is considering the Gulf of Mexico Fishery Management Council Amendments 36A and 36B which include several potential regulatory changes to the IFQ program. This study ﬁrst categorized these proposals into three basic groups and then examined each with respect to the potential impacts on six distinct commercial ﬁshing participant types. Key ﬁndings related to the potential eﬀects of each proposal are pre- sented in Table 4.

The ﬁrst set of proposals falls into two categories: permit require- ment proposals and share redistribution proposals. The most immediate impacts of these proposals would be on the “investor” participants and that impact would vary by investment size. Requiring a reef ﬁsh permit might dissuade small investors from purchasing quota, but would have little impact on large investors that could purchase a reef ﬁsh permit solely to own and lease out quota without signiﬁcantly lowering the returns on their quota investment. Analysis of share redistribution proposals demonstrated that such policies could lead to ﬂooded share markets as investors rush to disinvest before losing their privileges. While such a scenario would likely lead to lower share prices, there is no guarantee that allocation-dependent ﬁshers and supplementers would beneﬁt. It is possible that investor ﬁshers and pure ﬁshers might replace investors in the share market and purchase most of the share being sold by investors. If this were to happen, allocation-dependent ﬁshers would not gain an ownership stake in the ﬁshery and would be more constrained in purchasing allocation as the market would shrink. The second set of proposals are designed to prevent consolidation. While the red snapper IFQ program currently has a cap on quota shares that any single entity can own, there are no caps on allocation holdings or pounds harvested. Recent research has not, however, found high levels of concentration (Agar et al., 2014; Mitchell, 2016); moreover, between 2010 and 2014 the number of vessels harvesting red snapper has increased by 4.4% (NMFS, 2015). As such, these proposals do not seem justiﬁed at this time.

The third and ﬁnal set of proposals seeks to increase harvest ﬂex- ibility. One would remove the requirement to hold a commercial reef ﬁsh permit to land red snapper. The proposal, as written, does not re- strict other sectors (such as recreational and for-hire) from harvesting allocation and could lead to reallocation of catch between sectors. This study examined the proposal both with and without intersector trading. Without the possibility of intersector trading, the proposal would lessen the ﬁnancial requirements of new entrants to the ﬁshery by eliminating the requirement to purchase a commercial reef ﬁsh permit, but this is to the detriment of current ﬁshers who would see their permits become worthless. Moreover, it does nothing to reduce barriers to entry in terms of quota or allocation price. If intersector trading is allowed, which would open the quota market to non-permitted commercial and re- creational users, current permit holders would see their permits become worthless, but current share owners would see demand for share and allocation increase making their share investment more valuable. Allocation-dependent ﬁshers would be negatively impacted both by their permits becoming worthless and increased competition for share and allocation. While allocation-dependent ﬁshers might not be active in the share market, given the relatively constrained recreational ﬁshing seasons it seems reasonable to assume that recreational and for- hire ﬁshers that purchase share would do so with the intent of Ocean and Coastal Management 152 (2018) 48–56 Table 4 Potential eﬀects of the proposals. harvesting the allocation associated with it, thereby decreasing the pool of allocation available for commercial ﬁshers.

Another harvest ﬂexibility proposal considers the adoption of a roll- over provision for unused red snapper allocation that could lead to more allocation brokers in the IFQ market due to decreased risk of losses while holding allocation. In the past, late season quota increases - while see- mingly helpful to the ﬁshery - have led to market gluts at year end as ﬁshers race to use newly awarded allocation before it expires. The ad- ditional quota has negatively impacted allocation-dependent ﬁshers and allocation brokers that purchased prior to the quota increase when the supply of allocation was less and prices were higher. The GMFMC should realize that changing the annual quota midyear can have similar eﬀects to traditional crop reports where updated estimates of harvest levels are expected to have signiﬁcant impacts on stock values. In summary, there are two major takeaways from this study that apply not just to the red snapper IFQ program but other catch share programs considering changes. The ﬁrst is that design details are im- portant. While this may seem obvious it is worth stating since many changes have secondary impacts. For example, outcomes associated with share redistribution proposals would be dependent on share for- feiture rates. High forfeiture rates would lead to a sudden shift in share ownership as investors would rush to sell their quota share, while low forfeiture rates would likely lead to a more gradual shift in share ownership and limit decreased allocation market activity. Second, given the multiple participant types found in the IFQ program (in- vestors, brokers, allocation dependent ﬁshers, etc.), proposed changes can have unintended secondary consequences. As discussed, the pro- posals to increase share ownership among harvesters could negatively impact allocation-dependent ﬁshers if investor shareholdings are sold to other ﬁsher types (investor ﬁshers and pure ﬁshers) and the alloca- tion market dries up. With less allocation available and at higher prices, allocation-dependent ﬁshers and supplementers may see opportunities for landing red snapper decrease and be even more incentivized to discard.

This paper shows that suﬃcient information exists to make rea- sonable predictions of consequences for a suite of proposals to improve a catch share system. While improving how rights-based management programs perform is a noble goal, the development and implementation of program changes requires careful evaluation of how participants involved will react to change, how those reactions can inﬂuence out- comes, and how these outcomes align with legal requirements and program goals.
